  _solver_threads initialization:                                               
  self._solver_threads = os.cpu_count() or 1 if solver_threads == 0 else
  solver_threads                                                                
  Python conditional expression has lower precedence than or, so this parses as 
  (os.cpu_count() or 1) if solver_threads == 0 else solver_threads. That is what
   was intended. ✓                                                              
                  
  ---                                                                           
  2. Incremental cache — correctness analysis                                   
                                                                                
  Index integrity (c_idx matches list position):                                
  c_idx = len(self.columns[vue_id])   # index BEFORE append                     
  self.columns[vue_id].append(col)    # col now lives at index c_idx            
  _build_master_problem creates lam[(i, c_idx)] for c_idx in                    
  range(len(self.columns[i])). Since columns are never removed, every (vue_id,  
  c_idx) stored in _cell_users is always a valid key in lam at build time. ✓    
                                                                                
  _cell_users completeness — every column addition goes through _append_column  
  (confirmed above via grep). No column can be in self.columns without its cells
   being in _cell_users. ✓
                                                                                
  Null columns (cells=frozenset()) — the for cell in col.cells loop iterates    
  zero times. Null columns produce no _cell_users entries and no GB conflict
  checks. Identical to old behaviour. ✓                                         
                  
  _gb_conflicts — symmetry and completeness:                                    
  
  _columns_guard_band_conflict(c1, c2) is symmetric — the condition f2 < f1_end 
  + G and f1 < f2_end + G is unchanged when c1/c2 are swapped. So checking
  _columns_guard_band_conflict(new_col, existing_col) is equivalent to checking 
  the reverse.    

  Every ordered pair (col_A for VUE i, col_B for VUE j, i ≠ j) is checked       
  exactly once: when whichever of the two was registered later is appended, it
  checks against all already-registered columns of all other VUEs. This covers  
  the exact same pairs the old O(N²×C²×K²) loop covered. ✓

  Canonical ordering (vi_id < vj_id) in the set prevents the same physical pair 
  being stored in both orders as two separate entries. ✓
                                                                                
  _gb_conflicts → lam validity in integer master:                               
  (vi_id, ci) and (vj_id, cj) stored in _gb_conflicts were valid column indices
  when they were recorded. Since columns are never removed, they remain valid   
  when _build_master_problem(integer=True) runs. ✓
                                                                                
  ---             
  3. One real issue found: same-VUE resource constraints
                                                                                
  _cell_users[cell] can contain multiple entries for the same VUE if two columns
   from the same VUE both use that cell. Example: VUE 0 has col A and col B,    
  both occupying cell (5, 3):
                                                                                
  _cell_users[(5,3)] = [(0, 0), (0, 1)]   # both from VUE 0                     
                                                                                
  The len(users) > 1 check passes → a constraint lam[(0,0)] + lam[(0,1)] <= 1   
  gets added. This is redundant (the convexity constraint Σ_c lam[(0,c)] == 1   
  already implies only one can be non-zero), but not wrong.                     
                  
  The key question is whether the old code had the same behaviour — and it did: 
  # old code built the same users list:
  users = [(vue_id, c_idx) for vue ... for c_idx, col ... if cell in col.cells] 
  If two columns from VUE 0 used the same cell, the old code also added the same
   redundant constraint. This is a pre-existing issue, not a regression. ✓      
                                                                                
  ---                                                                           
  4. Performance tradeoff to be aware of                                        
                                                                                
  The old code ran all _columns_guard_band_conflict checks once in Phase 2. The
  new code runs them incrementally in _append_column during Phase 0 and Phase 1.
   The total number of _columns_guard_band_conflict calls is the same — just
  distributed differently. The per-call cost is identical.                      
                  
  The net trade is:                                                             
  - Removed: O(|cells| × N × C) Python dict membership checks per LP iteration
  (the expensive part)                                                          
  - Added: O(N × C_other × K²) GB checks per column added (fast integer
  arithmetic, same total as before)                                             
                                                                                
  For 6 VUEs, 20 cols, K=3, ~200 cells/col:
  - Removed per iteration: 648 cells × 6 × 20 = 77,760 set membership ops       
  - Added per iteration: 6 new cols × (5 VUEs × 20 cols × 9 slot pairs) = 5,400 
  int comparisons                                                               
                                                                                
  Clear net win, and the per-call GB check exits early on the first conflict it
  finds.                                                                        
                  
  ---                                                                           
  Verdict         
                                                                                
  No correctness bugs in either change. The implementations are logically sound
  and consistent with the original algorithm. The code can go to the cluster    
  as-is.          
                                                                                
  The one pre-existing issue (same-VUE redundant resource constraints) is not   
  introduced by this change and can be addressed separately if it ever shows up
  as a performance concern (it adds a trivially-tight constraint).              
                  
